# Code Standards

Applies to all coding sessions in this workspace. Teams can adapt as needed.

---

## Architecture Fit

- Read surrounding files before writing anything — match existing patterns exactly
- Same error handling style, service layering, IoC patterns, and consumer/handler structure
- A new function should be indistinguishable in style from the functions around it
- Default is to blend in — only refactor when there is a clear, justified reason

---

## Language and Tooling

- Check `package.json` and `.nvmrc` before writing — use only features available in the project's Node.js version
- TypeScript: explicit types, no `any`, no type assertions unless genuinely unavoidable
- `async/await` over raw promise chains
- Prefer utilities already in the project's dependencies — don't reimplement or add libraries without justification

---

## Function Design

- Under 20 lines where possible
- Single responsibility — one function does one thing
- If a function needs a comment to explain what it does, split or rename it

---

## JSDoc

Every new function must have a single-line JSDoc comment explaining *why* it exists or what business rule it encodes — not what the code literally does.

```ts
/** Skips comment sync when the ticket is closed, avoiding overwrite of resolved discussion. */
async function syncTicketComments(...) { ... }

/** Loads the caller's roles so auth middleware can reject requests outside the allowed set. */
function resolveAuthRoles(userId: string): Promise<string[]> { ... }
```

Skip if the function name already says it all.

---

## Error Handling

- Use typed error classes with explicit status codes — never throw generic `Error` from services
- Use `Result` objects with context-rich messages for validation failures
- Catch at the right level — don't swallow errors silently, don't rethrow without adding context

---

## No Dead Code

- No commented-out code, unused imports, or TODO comments in committed code
- If something is genuinely deferred, create a Jira ticket instead

---

## Logging

- `log.info` — significant state transitions (ticket created, ticket updated, comment posted)
- `log.warn` — recoverable issues needing attention (retryable API failure, deferred sync)
- `log.error` — failures with full context — include relevant IDs and ticket keys
- Never log PII or sensitive data
- No noisy debug logs in batch/event handlers — use `log.debug` at most

---

## TDD

- Write failing tests first — implementation follows
- 2-3 tests per function: happy path, key failure case, edge case
- Integration tests over excessive unit tests — test behaviour, not implementation
- Do not write tests for coverage numbers — write tests that catch real bugs
- Coverage targets: line ≥85%, branch ≥80%, function ≥90%

---

## Code Organisation

- 3-5 files per feature — not 15+ micro-files
- Static imports only — no dynamic imports unless justified
- 500-1,500 lines per file is acceptable — readable over rigid
- Abstract after 3+ occurrences — not before
